metadata.name: glory hole$ #310
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Bardez #264
metadata.description:
Bardez is the Armenian word for garden. It is etymologically tied to an ancient word for paradise, but that link goes deeper than etymology. Gardens have always been small pieces of paradise for me, and hearing the word in Armenian triggers a flood of warm memories.

Memories of wandering around my grandfather’s garden, plucking ripe plums and figs from their branches.
Memories of playing in my parents yard, the scent of jasmine in the summer heat.
Of sun warmed tomatoes in my mom’s vegetable patch.
The smell of dirt and grass.
Mud on my hands.
Sun on my skin.
Memories of paradise.

I hope you enjoy these gardens I’ve planted, and I hope they remind you of some warm and wonderful memories.
 
Nat Sarkissian






Notes:
 - This piece uses a shader to compute the lighting of the terrain in the first frame. If you don’t have a graphics card, you may have difficulty running this.

 - Append “&mag=N” to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you the progress of the render, and also show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

 - Finally, collectors at the highest tier will be entitled to a signed print of their edition. For further details and updates, keep an eye on my Twitter (@_NatSarkissian).

metadata.name: Shape Study  #115
metadata.description:
“Everyone has their own shape.”
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone’s collection.

“Why do they need to have so many similar things?”

Perhaps it’s their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they’re meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what’s visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It’s only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

『每個人都有自己的形狀』
並且每個人一生中也會認識各種形狀

程式的隨機性讓我產生的每個形狀都相似而不同
我想像這也許是某個人的蒐藏
『為什麼會需要擁有這麼多相似的道具呢？』

也許是它們有著不同的功能，能帶來不同的愉悅；
也許是適用於不同的場景
也許是遲遲未找到屬於自己的形狀

想像至此，我意識到：當人們探索自己／他人的同時，也可以說是一種形狀研究
用一個看得見的具體，去探索一個看不見的抽象

然而，好的形狀是可遇不可求的
其實形狀本身沒有好壞，只有當兩個形狀相遇時，形狀才有了意義
希望蒐藏這件作品的各位都可以遇到喜歡的形狀

metadata.name: 10SCII #179
metadata.description:
10SCII is my take on the famous 10 PRINT program.

10 PRINT CHR$(205.5+RND(1)); : GOTO 10 is a single line program that produces a simple but visually appealing set of forward and backward slashes.

This project riffs on the original idea by removing the vertical space between lines and widening the horizontal gap. This changes the produced pieces from a maze of slashes into a series of towers. This is then rendered and animated as ASCII.

Visit https://10print.org/ to learn more about the original program that inspired this piece.

metadata.name: Vertical World #68
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #745
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.
